	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>PC overheat?</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />My PC is suffering a weird behaviour. Let me give an example: Windows Movie Maker. When it starts rendering my new video, the CPU usage goes nearby 100%, and the PC temperature raises... until the moment of becoming very very slow... and it shuts down. Another example is watching YouTube fHD videos - a bit less, but still stays slow after a few minutes.<br /><br />I wonder a solution for it (instead of buy a new PC - yup, my laptop doesn't have such problem... and I used it for rendering my video).

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>thefox</b> [ Thu Jan 15, 2015 8:34 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: PC overheat?</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />When the CPU temperature rises, modern CPUs will try to underclock themselves (=&gt; slowdown) to keep the temperature within limits. In case the temperature still manages to reach a certain threshold, it will shut itself down as a safety measure.<br /><br />Try cleaning your CPU fan with compressed air and make sure it's properly seated. Some diagnostic applications can be useful in finding out the CPU frequency and temperature.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
